 the European level. It also offers a more accurate appraisal of the official characterisation of the terrorist threat within the EU as a 'matter of common concern'. In doing so, not only does it raise important questions about the utility of the European level for organising internal security co-operation, but it also provides a more comprehensive assessment of the EU's activities throughout the lifetime of the Third Pillar, placing in a wider and more realistic context the EU's reaction to the events of 11 September 2001 and the greater prominence of Islamist terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolicexEuropean Union countries. 0aPolicezEuropean Union countries. 0aSecurity, InternationalzEuropean Union countries. 0aTerrorismxEuropean Union countriesxPrevention. 0aTerrorismzEuropean Union countriesxPrevention. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh  aEuropean Police Office.  aEuropean Union.  aIslamist terrorism.  aThird Pillar.  acounter-terrorism.  ainformation exchange.  ainternal security.  apolice co-operation.  apolicing.  aterrorist threat.1 aBrown, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779273040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792730/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles